We play games of systems not to reduce them, not to suggest they are unreal, not to forget the violence they cause.</p>
<p>We play games of systems because games can change.</p>
<p>
  When we play a game of a system, this shows us that systems can change too.
  We can mod a system to create a different one.
</p>
<p>When we know what we're trying to build, the kind of system we want to create, we can use this to guide us.</p>
/* / */

<p>We can use games to look to the future, to imagine how things could be different.</p>
<p>Games can also remind us how flawed and broken things are. Like the extraction economy game did in our last session. </p>
<p>They can remind us that we're living in a system that destroys our Earth by pulling things out of it.</p>
<p>That this system serves those with power. </p>
/* / */
<p>And changing games reminds us that things can be different.</p>
<p>It reminds us that change is possible.</p>
<p>Isn’t it time we played a different game?</p>

